title: For Sale:  Virginian dragoon .44 magnum
postcontent: Great .44 magnum single action pistol in good shape, shoot me a text or email if you're interestedprice is $400 firm, comes with nice plastic caseREDACTED These were manufactured in Alexandria, Virginia. The Hitchner Corporation cast a heavy revolver frame using 4140 Steel, app. 10% more substantial than its contemporaries- Ruger Blackhawk and S&W. These Dragoon revolvers were built to very close tolerances and hand fitted and individually tuned and lock up tighter than almost any other single action ever made, similar to the individual quality of the colt line of Pythons. The large bolt and cylinder stops contribute greatly to these quality features. A Swiss Safety was incorporated into the design along with cylinder dots drilled to the left and right of one bore to indicate the empty chamber, also quite unique to the Dragoon. The revolver has adjustable rear sights with walnut grips that show no sign of wear. Other features include one piece back strap, brazed front sight, recessed cylinders, coil mainspring, internal firing pin, split grip panels, and unlike Ruger, Interarms used a locked firing pin busing on the Dragoon. The list price in the early 80's when this was made was 280.00 whereas the Blackhawk, 10% less substantial in structure, was only 200.00. The cost of hand fitting and tuning each one of these Dragoons individually along with other excellent unique features left the Dragoon at a price point of $80.00 above the MSRP of the Blackhawk. These extras put an impact on the overall sales of the Dragoon and production was haulted in 1985.

Cerakoted.  The Slide, frame and mainspring houseing are Tungsten (metallic dark grey), all other parts and pins are Cobalt (metallic black).  It's a pretty slick looking firearm.  It comes with 3 mags.  One Springfield 7 round that works great, an 8 round ACT mag that could use a new spring.  The first round tends to nose dive but cycles fine after that.  Also a 10 round promag that I picked up in a trade.  It looked like someone went at with some pliers and I was rather skeptical of it.  It worked surprising well though.  Sticks a bit on the release.  As you can see, quite a bit of work has been put into this little fella and I'm asking a more than fair price. So no lowball offers please.
